  "text": "The literature has considered both costs and benefits of legal uncertainty. Legal uncertainty reduces deterrence and makes it more difficult or impossible to achieve optimal 3 See European Commission (2010) and Regulation No. 330/2010 for details. 4 An alternative source of legal uncertainty for vertical restraints are assessments of efficiency defenses. Then circumstances would measure the amount of efficiencies of an action. deterrence. For example, [CITATION_1] demonstrate that legal uncertainty lowers deterrence, because expected sanctions are reduced and less suits are brought to court. [CITATION_2] analyze firms' strategic responses to legal uncertainty in competition law. They show that both type I and type II errors lower deterrence. Png (1986) and Polinsky and Shavell (2000, Section 8) show how to adjust sanctions for type I and type II errors. [CITATION_3] discusses whether type I errors influence deterrence.",
